Chemical Release Prevention Program
Santa Fe has a chemical release prevention program in place for the chlorination process.  Key provisions of the prevention program are as follows:

1. Written procedures have been prepared for the chlorination process, including directions for safe startup and shutdown operations and emergency shutdown;

2. Employees who operate the chlorination system must receive training initially and periodically on safe startup and shutdown operations and emergency shutdown;

3. Incidences, including minor releases are investigated to improve the safety of the chlorination process;

4. Once completed, incident investigations are shared with employees;

5. A hazard review, which identifies potential hazards and ways to improve the safety of the chlorination process, is conducted every five years, or when significant changes are made to the process;

6. A maintenance program is in place to prevent accidental chemical releases that may result from mechanical failure of improperly maintained equipment.  Maintenance practices are consistent with guidance provided by the Chlorine Institute; and

7. Compliance audits are conducted every three years to evaluate the RMProgram and its implementation for compliance with the EPA RMP Standard.

